    <p class="top-text">
        Experience a traditional Sri Lankan meal catered by Rasai and
        taste the complexity and the richness of Sri Lankan culture.
        Rasia believes in the authentic preparation and freshness of
        Sri Lankan food, and source many of the ingredients from farmer’s
        markets, our own vegetable garden, specifically stores and local butchers.
    </p>

    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/1Ambulthiyal.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Abulthiyal (fish ambul thiyal)</h3>
            <p>
                Ambulthiyal, also known as malu ambulthiyal is a must-try Sri Lankan
                sour fish curry. Made with Goraka (dried garcinia) and black pepper,
                not only gives the fish ambulthiyal (sour fish) curry a unique taste but
                is also a method of preserving fish without refrigeration or freezing.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/2Kukul-Mas-Curry.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Kukul mas curry (chicken curry)</h3>
            <p>
                Kukul mas is a Colombo-style tradition Sri Lankan chicken curry.
                This creamy and lightly spiced curry is typically made with diced chicken breast,
                onions, ginger, garlic, turmeric, garam masala, chilli powder, coconut milk,
                tomatoes, oil, and salt.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/3Parippu.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Parippu (dhal curry)</h3>
            <p>
                Parippu Curry is basically a Moong Lentil Curry, tempered in a typical South Indian style.
                It has a good dose of coconut, just like any other dish in this part of our country,
                and other spices.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/4Polos.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Polos (green Jackfruit curry)</h3>
            <p>
                Polos curry or polos ambula is a traditional Sri Lankan baby jackfruit curry.
                This jackfruit curry is made using jackfruit which has not matured or ripped,
                at this stage of the jackfruit, the fruit is often referred to as baby jackfruit
                or green jackfruit.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/5Wambatu-Moju.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Wambatu moju (eggplant/brinjals pickle)</h3>
            <p>
                Wambatu moju aka brinjal moju are fried eggplant strips, shallots, and
                green chillies mixed with mustard vinegar to pickle them, giving it a combo of sweet, sour, and heat.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/6Gotu-Kola-Sambol.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Gotu kola sambol (pennywort salad)</h3>
            <p>
                A green salad with chopped Gotu kola and freshly scraped coconut gives
                you one of the healthiest salads in Sri Lankan cuisine.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/7Kottu.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Kottu (also kottu roti)</h3>
            <p>
                Kottu translates from Sinhalese as chopped, and this hugely popular Sri Lankan street
                food consists of chopped up roti (a type of flatbread), stir-fried with chicken, vegetables and egg.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/8Lamprais.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Lamprais</h3>
            <p>
                Lamprais is a Sri Lankan meal, a marriage of multiple elements – samba rice,
                brinjal and meat curries, seeni sambol, fried ash plantain and blachan – steamed
                and packed in a banana leaf. Lamprais recipes have typically been a burgher family
                tradition. It is a meal with a strong, yet gradually wavering legacy.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/9Hoppers.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Hoppers (appa or appam)</h3>
            <p>
                An appa or appam is a type of thin pancake originating from South India and Sri Lanka,
                It is made with fermented rice batter and coconut milk, traditionally cooked in an
                appachatti, a deep pan similar in shape to a wok.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <img class="food" src="/lib/10Pol-Sambol.png" alt="Food"></a>
        <div class="text-content">
            <h3>Pol Sambol (coconut relish)</h3>
            <p>
                It is a coconut relish, consisting of fresh grated coconut, shallots, dried whole chillies or
                chili powder, lime juice, and salt.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

